                <outline text="I'm stealing a prompt from the 642 Tiny Things to Write About book that Christina gave me. Here are the two parts of the prompt: Where would you choose to be exiled? What three essential items would you take with you?" _note=" " />
                <outline text="If I'm exiled, I'm guessing I wouldn't have a whole lot of control over traveling...so I'd want to pick a place that I could see myself staying for a while. I'm not sure this is the best answer, but right now Iceland keeps popping up in my mind. There's a lot of bad aspects of that answer...harsh weather, new language, etc. But it's pretty remote, and I feel like that's a good component of an exiled land. I'm probably sick of people if I'm getting kicked out... ;)" _note=" " />
                <outline text="The first thing that I'd take is a camera. Probably my Fuji X100S. Iceland is too beautiful to not photograph. Especially if you're exiled there. Next, I'd take my Kindle. If I'm exiled, I'd read a fuckton. Finally, I'd definitely need a computer. I could code, work, research, etc. with a computer at virtually any location with an Internet connection." /></outline>

              <outline text="&lt;b&gt;## Morning Pages #MorningPages&lt;/b&gt;" >
                <outline text="I had a lot of anger yesterday afternoon and evening. I'm not sure exactly where it started, but it really built up by technological issues. Rodeo isn't working on my Mac (can't install packages), and it really made me mad. It wasn't the sort of thing that really had cause to make me super mad, though, so I think it was more of a straw that broke the camel's back situation. " _note=" " />
                <outline text="Now that I'm looking back on it, I think maybe the irritation came when I was talking to Megan and hearing my feedback. It's weird...I don't think that much positive feedback has ever made me feel so frustrated. Basically, she said that she's been really happy with pretty much everything that I've done and all the progress I've made. Great news, right? Well, kind of. But that also implies that being promoted from now on will have a great deal to do with things that are outside my control. Which isn't promising, given my abnormal career path." _note=" " />
                <outline text="Regardless, letting that frustration get to me and affect my behavior as much as it did yesterday is not good! In hindsight, I should have caught myself and done a 20 minute meditation or something to reset me. Oh well. I can't beat myself up about it too much. We all get angry sometimes, and no serious harm was done this time around. Just learnings for next time!" /></outline>
              <outline text="Book Quote" >
                <outline text="&lt;u&gt;Peace is Every Step&lt;/u&gt;: https://workflowy.com/#/0b7c02407aa9" />
                <outline text="&amp;gt; &quot;If you have lost your smile and yet are still capable of seeing that a dandelion is keeping it for you, the situation is not too bad. You still have enough mindfulness to see that the smile is there. You only need to breathe consciously one or two times and you will recover your smile.&quot; -- Thich Nhat Hanh, p. 7-8" /></outline>

              <outline text="&lt;b&gt;## Morning Pages #MorningPages&lt;/b&gt;" >
                <outline text="Yesterday was a bit of a rough one. Serious lack of motivation. Probably a hangover from such a productive Monday. It's interesting how that works out. It might be better to just have a few generally productive days than to burn yourself out one day and then have a poorly productive day the next. I mean, obviously that's true. The question is how far should you push it before you burn out? I think that if there's something fun at the end of the day, it can do wonders to prevent burn out. For example, making dinner and watching something with Christina or going and seeing a sunset. Not studying. Studying for these god damn exams and courses is so frustrating." _note=" " />
                <outline text="(Recalls affirmation of the day...feels guilty...stops complaining) :)" /></outline>
              <outline text="Book Quote" >
                <outline text="&lt;u&gt;Peace is Every Step&lt;/u&gt;: https://workflowy.com/#/0b7c02407aa9" />
                <outline text="&amp;gt; &quot;We are too undemanding, too ready to watch whatever is on the screen, too lonely, lazy, or bored to create our own lives. We turn on the TV and leave it on, allowing someone else to guide us, shape us, and destroy us.&quot; -- Thich Nhat Hanh, p. 14" /></outline>

              <outline text="ISPs rated on an item level" />
              <outline text="Class Code 4, 5, and 6 are used for ISPs" >
                <outline text="Assumption:" >
                  <outline text="4 is # of minor violations" />
                  <outline text="5 is # of accidents" />
                  <outline text="6 is # of major violations" /></outline>

              <outline text="PHF uses policy that has the highest violations, etc. to populate the fields" /></outline>

                <outline text="&lt;b&gt;**I am grateful for...**  &lt;/b&gt;" >
                  <outline text="1. " />

              </outline>
              <outline text="&lt;b&gt;## Morning Pages #MorningPages&lt;/b&gt;" />
              <outline text="Book Quote" >
                <outline text="&lt;u&gt;Peace is Every Step&lt;/u&gt;: https://workflowy.com/#/0b7c02407aa9" />
                <outline text="&amp;gt; &quot;&quot; -- Thich Nhat Hanh, p. " /></outline>
            </outline>
          </outline>
          <outline text="&lt;b&gt;Health&lt;/b&gt;" >
            <outline text="Meal Log #4HB " >
              <outline text="Breakfast: " />
              <outline text="Lunch: " />
              <outline text="Dinner: " />
              <outline text="Snack: " /></outline>
            <outline text="Pushups: 45 #tinygains " /></outline>
          <outline text="&lt;b&gt;Events&lt;/b&gt;" />
          <outline text="&lt;b&gt;Tasks&lt;/b&gt;" />
          <outline text="&lt;b&gt;Notes &lt;/b&gt;" >
            <outline text="Presentation " >
              <outline text="Intro" >
                <outline text="Agenda" >
                  <outline text="Status Update" />
                  <outline text="Talk through some of the results so far and get Jeff's thoughts" />
                  <outline text="Talk about next steps" /></outline>
              </outline>
              <outline text="Status Update" >
                <outline text="Through ~1.5 iterations of the SA" />
                <outline text="I ran an initial &quot;base SA&quot; using the legacy SAS code and Excel workbook. This was the first iteration of the SA, and it consisted of running a lot of data prep code to get the PHF data ready for the SA. We haven't run a SA in a while, and we haven't had an analyst look at the code very closely from start to finish, and as a result I had to do quite a bit of maintenance on this legacy code. For example, I had to implement code for the teenSMART discount, which was new since our last SA. I also encountered some issues with the underlying data in this process, including missing codes for the multiline (life) discounts. " />
                <outline text="This process is very time-consuming and manual. Analyzing a single rating plan within this structure consisted of running a section of SAS code, waiting ~20-30 minutes, copying the results into an Excel workbook, analyzing the indicated factors and making selections, and copying the updated factors back into SAS. " />
                <outline text="Part of my project has been to refresh this process with new technologies and programming approaches to allow for more automation. With the new approach, I have the option to work in an iterative fashion similar to the legacy approach (necessary if you don't know what selections you want to make), but I also have the option to set some inputs up front and run an entire SA with the click of a button. For example, the new approach allows for running a full scenario with selected = indicated with a single click. There are a lot of other benefits of the new approach, but the biggest one is probably that we'll be able to run more iterations in a given timeframe, which will hopefully give us more information to aid our decision-making." />
                <outline text="Roughly 95% of this new code has been written and tested. I was hoping to have it completed by this meeting and have a full second iteration of the SA completed by this meeting, but I unearthed an additional issue last week that's slowed progress in the final steps. I'll discuss it a bit more later on, but at a high level we're missing Mileage data on a significant chunk of our customers. Because Mileage is one of the first steps in the SA, and because all subsequent analysis depends on the results of Mileage, the results for most of the rating plans shouldn't be taken too seriously at this point. I would guess that we'll see directionally similar results for most of the rating plans after fixing Mileage, but I'd rather wait until it's fixed before diving too deep into some of the rating plans. We can still go over some results at a high level, but I just wanted to highlight that caveat up front." /></outline>
              <outline text="Results" >
                <outline text="ISPs" >
                  <outline text="Background on ISP calculations for accidents" />
                  <outline text="In general, the spread between no accidents and a first accident is in line with indicated. For example, the indicated spread between no ISP points (no accidents) and a single accident (ISP group 5: 2-2) weighted by premium is 79%, whereas current factors are at a 78% spread." />
                  <outline text="We can reduce this spread somewhat by making modifications to levels where possible, but we're limited by needing to stay within current and indicated at each level" /></outline>
                <outline text="Mileage" >
                  <outline text="This is the first running of a SA since the implementation of verified mileage" />
                  <outline text="I want to reiterate that these mileage results should just be considered rough preliminary results, as roughly 15% of our exposures have missing mileage data. I'm working through getting a fix with the PHF folks, but for now these exposures are just slotted in the 12k mileage band. This is likely introducing some bias into the weights calculations, and likely has the effect of making the mileage weights lower than they really are. " />
                  <outline text="Even with the likely bias towards smaller weights, the current mileage weights are greater than they were with our last filing. This was an expected result of the implementation of VM, but it's nice to see it playing out in the data. " /></outline>
                <outline text="Years Licensed/Marital/Gender Weights" >
                  <outline text="Historical Calculation vs. Current Calculation" />
                  <outline text="Impact" >
                    <outline text="It's tough to tell exactly what the full extent of the impact will be since the Mileage distribution is uncertain and the Mileage weight is likely understated at this point, but it seems likely that Years Licensed is going to be capped for some coverages." />
                    <outline text="This means that we'll likely have to reduce spread in YL and/or increase spread in Mileage, but it also means that we'll have more freedom to increase spread where indicated in the non-required rating plans (e.g., territory)" /></outline>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Multiline" >
                  <outline text="Looks like there's opportunity to deepen the discounts for Owners, but because multiline comes after the Mileage step it's possible that this could change after Mileage is fixed." />
                  <outline text="It's also important to remember that our Owners book is pretty old at this point, so the current indicated discounts may not be reflective of what will be indicated when we have newer business mixed in. The NB Owners/Auto customers may have different experience than the long-renewing Owners/Auto customers that underlie this data. As such, I think it might be wise not to go fully to indicated on this discount." /></outline>
              </outline>
              <outline text="Next Steps" >
                <outline text="Finish running this second iteration" >
                  <outline text="Finish writing code (territory, weights for Years Licensed, etc.)" />
                  <outline text="Incorporate fix for Mileage" />
                  <outline text="Update selections" /></outline>
                <outline text="Run more iterations to sensitivity test, better target business objectives, etc." />
                <outline text="Incorporate Matthew's territorial models" />
                <outline text="Investigate other rating plans in more detail" />
                <outline text="Transition the rest of the SA code to R (e.g., data prep)" /></outline>
            </outline>

              <outline text="&lt;b&gt;## Morning Pages #MorningPages&lt;/b&gt;" >
                <outline text="I had a really good talk with my parents this morning. It's interesting how sometimes we'll have really good talks about topics that are interesting and we're both engaged in...and then other times we never really get into the swing of a discussion. Having a good topic to get the conversation started is really important. It'd be a good habit to develop to kind of have a running log of conversation starters. Not the typical &quot;good weather&quot; bullshit, but topics of interest that have been on your mind lately or something." /></outline>

              <outline text="Slides" >
                <outline text="Introduction to Excel Basics" >
                  <outline text="We have some training sessions that are focused on teaching you things and some sessions that are kind of a hybrid between teaching and acting as a reference guide. This presentation falls into the latter category. So our goal with this training session isn't necessarily going to be to teach you how to use Excel...but rather to give you a feel for the landscape of Excel. We want you to have a sense of the tools that are available in Excel so that when you start getting your hands dirty with projects you'll have a good starting point for your Googling and research. With that in mind, I'm going to be breezing through some of these sections pretty quickly, but I'd encourage you to save a copy of this presentation in your Documents somewhere (e.g., Documents/Helpful Things/Tools/Excel) so that you can use it as a reference guide when you're working. Feel free to slow me down or ask any questions that come to mind though!" />
                  <outline text="Also, I'm fighting off a cold, so if I randomly stop talking I'm probably just taking a drink of water or something. You'll have to bear with me on my incessent throat clearing..." /></outline>

                  <outline text="Another thing to be cautious of is double clicking to extend a formula down a column when there are missing records in the adjacent column." /></outline>

                <outline text="Introduction to Excel Basics" >
                  <outline text="We have some training sessions that are focused on teaching you things and some sessions that are kind of a hybrid between teaching and acting as a reference guide. This presentation falls into the latter category. So our goal with this training session isn't necessarily going to be to teach you how to use Excel...but rather to give you a feel for the landscape of Excel. We want you to have a sense of the tools that are available in Excel so that when you start getting your hands dirty with projects you'll have a good starting point for your Googling and research. With that in mind, I'm going to be breezing through some of these sections pretty quickly, but I'd encourage you to save a copy of this presentation in your Documents somewhere (e.g., Documents/Helpful Things/Tools/Excel) so that you can use it as a reference guide when you're working. Feel free to slow me down or ask any questions that come to mind though!" /></outline>

              <outline text="&lt;b&gt;## Morning Pages #MorningPages&lt;/b&gt;" >
                <outline text="We slept in today and were pretty lazy in the morning. I woke up an hour or two ahead of Christina and Andrew and read War and Peace for an hour. It was nice to just hang out and do nothing for a change. We had a really excellent and busy day yesterday, so relaxing felt nice. " _note=" " />
                <outline text="I'm writing this at a very beautiful lake that Andrew likes to run around. It's just outside the city wall in Nanjing, and it's really busy. We're sitting on a pathway that's off the main paths next to a lily pond and people are walking by us every 15 seconds or so. " _note=" " />
                <outline text="A lot of people have been staring at us today. It's a weird feeling to possibly be the first white person that some of these little kids have seen. We're collecting a lot of stares..." _note=" " />
                <outline text="A girl has a dress that says &quot;Love sees roses without thrones.&quot; There have been a lot of silly English sayings on shirts over here, but a handful of them have actually been pretty insightful and deep. There are some opera singers somewhere off in the distance. Another man has a shirt that says &quot;Life is a continuous process of remaining ourselves.&quot; Another has one that says &quot;Internet.&quot; Like I said, some ridiculous shirts and a few insightful ones..." _note=" " />
                <outline text="We've had so many pictures taken of us on this trip. Lots of staring and people trying to be sneaky with their phones. Most people are much less sneaky than they think they are... It's interesting that the universal reaction to being &quot;caught&quot; is to smile guiltily. There are parts of human culture that transcend language." _note=" " />
                <outline text="----" _note=" " />
                <outline text="We went to the English Corner this evening, which is where Chinese people go to learn English. I talked for almost an hour with a nice 8th grade girl named Mariah who's from the same province as Huangshan (the Yellow Mountains). " _note=" " /></outline>

              <outline text="&lt;b&gt;## Morning Pages #MorningPages&lt;/b&gt;" >
                <outline text="I'm back in the United States! Christina and I flew into Omaha yesterday morning from Dallas after our overnight layover. It feels weird to be back home, but it's a really good weird. Travel is excellent for pushing boundaries, but it's also good to have period of relaxation and recovery. I can already sense some of the nasty habits of being home percolating, though. For example, I had a few beers and watched a movie last night. This was a pattern that I was recognizing at the end of my days before I left that I want to break. Fortunately, I was aware that I was making that choice last night and decided to do so because it was my last &quot;cheat day&quot; before getting started on the slow carb diet again today. I think sticking to that diet will help prevent those habits from starting up again because I won't be able to have any beer except on cheat days. This should have a nice cascading effect." _note=" " />
                <outline text="Speaking of the slow carb diet, I'm sipping on a version of [Tim Ferris's morning cocktail](http://fourhourworkweek.com/2015/05/25/morning-tea-thats-better-than-coffee/) instead of my usual black coffee. I was listening to his podcast with Dom D'agostino while I was at Whole Foods yesterday and he was talking about incorporating coconut oil into your diet for its medium chain triglycerides and about how grass fed butter is basically a super food and thought &quot;what the heck, I'll try a version of this bulletproof coffee&quot; and picked up some coconut oil and grass fed butter. I added about a tablespoon of each to my coffee yesterday afternoon and blended it up and thought it tasted delicious. So this morning I'm trying adding both to a tea blend of pu-erh tea and green tea. I steeped the Rishi pu-erh tea (not willing to use the pu-erh I bought in China in this recipe just yet) for two minutes before adding Tazo organic pan-fried green tea and steeping for another three minutes. I then added the tea and a tablespoon of the butter and coconut oil to the blender and blended on &quot;liquify&quot; for 20 seconds. I steeped the tea in my Hydro Flask and poured it back into the Hydro Flask after blending and fortunately the heat loss has been minimal. I've been sipping on it for about 40 minutes now and it's still warm (and I haven't had the cap on at all). " _note=" " />
                <outline text="Enough writing in the journal for now, though. I'm going to switch gears and do some writing for my blog now! Need to get a second blog post up about China, and I can finally do so now that I've got all my pictures imported to my Mac Pro's Lightroom Library." /></outline>
              <outline text="Book Quote" >
                <outline text="&lt;u&gt;Peace is Every Step&lt;/u&gt;: https://workflowy.com/#/0b7c02407aa9" />
                <outline text="&amp;gt; &quot;&quot; -- Thich Nhat Hanh, p. " /></outline>

              <outline text="&lt;b&gt;## Morning Pages #MorningPages&lt;/b&gt;" >
                <outline text="I put up a blog post about China yesterday. It feels really good to get something up. I've noticed a pretty strong psychic angst against blog posts lately. My photo of the week project has definitely dropped off lately, for example. When the weekend comes I'm just not that interested in writing something and putting up an image. I think it's partly a resistance to writing and partly a confusion about what I'm trying to accomplish with my photography. Is it just for fun or am I possibly wanting to get some money out of the whole thing? If it's the latter, then there's pressure on me to put up really good images that can lead somewhere. I think I've been interested in this idea for a while, but I want to make sure that I don't sacrifice my love for photography in the process." _note=" " />
                <outline text="Now that I'm back in the office, it's going to be interesting to see how things proceed with the possibility of working for Adam. To be honest, I'm really scared. I haven't been this scared about anything work related probably since I started. Switching to CA was scary, but I had people like Lindsay and Corey working in personal lines that I could model myself after. I knew that if they could do it, so could I. With this job, I feel totally unprepared. I guess that's not true. Hmm...well, I &lt;i&gt;*know*&lt;/i&gt; that I'm not totally unprepared, but I kind of &lt;i&gt;*feel*&lt;/i&gt; like that's the case. That's just something I'm going to have to get over." /></outline>

                <outline text="I've noticed that I'm not really into a lot of what I'm doing at work now that I'm back. It's just not a whole lot of fun and I'm not enthused. I think this is probably a sign that I need to get more invested in it. The work itself isn't really that boring...I'm just allowing myself to be bored by it. I'm going to try to view it from a more optimistic mindset and find ways to be interested and excited by it next week. I need to lean in!" /></outline>

              <outline text="&lt;b&gt;## Morning Pages #MorningPages&lt;/b&gt;" >
                <outline text="I listened to Brene Brown's Power of Vulnerability TED talk this morning. It was prompted by a quote of hers that went along the lines of &quot;you cannot selectively numb emotion...when you numb the bad things you also numb the good things.&quot; This reminded me of a talk with Lindsay a while ago about that very topic. I was arguing that there had to be a way to be selective about these things... I still struggle with this notion. If we can't selectively feel different emotions, how do we manage our lives and achieve a self-sustaining &quot;happiness&quot; (or whatever word we want to use for a pleasant, well-adjusted life)?" _note=" " />
                <outline text="In Buddhism, to my outsider eyes it seems like they try to numb all emotions. It's like they try to accept all emotions as they are and not change anything. If we don't try to change anything, though, then do we end up just being incredibly passive and letting life pass us by? Don't we want to strive for something better? For example, if I'm an alcoholic don't I want to &lt;b&gt;**do**&lt;/b&gt; something about that rather than just &quot;accept me for me&quot;? I'm sure there are nuances that I'm missing here...gonna need to do some more research." /></outline>
              <outline text="Book Quote" >
                <outline text="&lt;u&gt;Peace is Every Step&lt;/u&gt;: https://workflowy.com/#/0b7c02407aa9" />
                <outline text="&amp;gt; &quot;&quot; -- Thich Nhat Hanh, p. " /></outline>
            </outline>

              <outline text="&lt;b&gt;## Morning Pages #MorningPages&lt;/b&gt;" >
                <outline text="I'm sensing a bit of a sadness in myself. I noticed it the other day when I was talking to Christina about some of my old friendships (Amelia and Lindsay, specifically). I had a little realization that I'm much more of a loner now than I have been maybe at any other time in my life. Since I went remote, I haven't been very close to any of my Chicago friends (Lindsay was the sharpest drop-off). All of my college friends were more or less given the same treatment when I moved to Chicago. And hardly any of my high school friends remain. And now, I haven't really added any new friends with this latest change. " _note=" " />
                <outline text="I think this probably gets harder/less natural as you get older. For one, there's a smaller pool of people available. Once people get married and start having kids and building their own families, their room for friends drops. What room they have is allocated to their long-time friends, not gambled on some new person. And there just aren't as many opportunities as an adult. When you're in school, you're constantly forced together with people your own age. It happens to some degree at work, but there's often more of a barrier between co-workers than there is between students." /></outline>
              <outline text="Book Quote" >
                <outline text="&lt;u&gt;Peace is Every Step&lt;/u&gt;: https://workflowy.com/#/0b7c02407aa9" />
                <outline text="&amp;gt; &quot;&quot; -- Thich Nhat Hanh, p. " /></outline>

                <outline text="I got a Leica M3 yesterday, and it's quite a beautiful machine. I had a blast wandering around and shooting with it. It doesn't have a meter, and the meter that came with it doesn't seem to be working, so I had to do a lot of guesswork when setting the exposure...which was kind of fun in a lot of ways.                 <outline text="I'm home in Colorado for the weekend. It's nice to be back and see my family. My dad is rafting down the Grand Canyon, so it's a unique experience to just be hanging out with my mom. It's nice to have some time where it's just us. I feel like I get these experiences with my dad periodically because we have bike rides and hikes and sports (or we used to at least) that we can do together. But that stuff doesn't happen as naturally with my mom, so we don't always have time where it's just us. Having Keegan lose his mom (or...is in the process of losing his mom) is a timely reminder to fully appreciate this time since you never know how many more of these times you'll have in the future. Sounds kind of morbid when I write it down, but I'm trying not to think of it that way...more in the way of just being reminded to appreciate the moment you do have..." /></outline>

              <outline text="&lt;b&gt;## Morning Pages #MorningPages&lt;/b&gt;" >
                <outline text="I had a pretty good day yesterday. Christina and I are in kind of a weird spot. I feel like she's missing something from our relationship...like she wants something that she doesn't quite feel that she's getting. It seems to revolve around romantic gestures and things. I suppose that's something that I need to be better about. I get a little defensive on that topic because I feel like it's easy to go over the top on that sort of stuff and end up de-valuing it. Then you have to become **more** romantic to produce the same effect, and it's a never-ending cycle that you can never keep up with and you'll inevitably end up disappointing her. Why can't we just appreciate each other for who we are and what we have now? Why do we need to be prompted by some romantic gesture to do that?" _note=" " />
                <outline text="Anyways, it was a good day. We went to her Grandma Rita's birthday party and her aunt's (Mary Jo...so many names!) and I had quite a bit of fun. It was nice to talk to her family...which was a little surprising. I wasn't expecting to enjoy it as much as I did. I meditated before we left to kind of center myself and calm myself, and I think that helped out a lot. Gotta remember that for next time..." /></outline>

              <outline text="&lt;b&gt;## Morning Pages #MorningPages&lt;/b&gt;" >
                <outline text="Can you practice feeling? I've noticed that I have some resistance to feeling certain things or remembering certain occasions because they're almost *too* special. I feel like they're sacred events, and I worry that remembering them or experiencing those powerful memories when I recall the events to memory will devalue them. Like pizza is really amazing if you only have it every once in awhile...but if you have it for every meal it's nothing special. Scarcity can create a feeling of value. So does frequently recalling those memories devalue the memories? " _note=" " />
                <outline text="Perhaps. I'm undecided on that front. There's a flip side that I might be missing out on by not recalling those memories, too... Maybe trying to recall that same exact memory every time will devalue it over time...or maybe by practicing that feeling of whatever it was when you were there in that memory will strengthen it. Is that how feelings work? Are they like a muscle, where the more you practice feeling them the more powerful you'll feel them? Hmm...that's something to explore..." _note=" " /></outline>

              <outline text="&lt;b&gt;## Morning Pages #MorningPages&lt;/b&gt;" >
                <outline text="I woke up this morning around 2:45 and couldn't get back to sleep. So I got up at about 3:30 and now here I am at 4:15 journaling. It's funny how our circadian rhythms work. It feels pretty good to be up at this time of day. It's so peaceful, and there's something really satisfying about getting a head start on the day. I wonder if that's just achievement oriented thinking...am I feeling satisfied about this situation because I feel like I'm &quot;getting ahead&quot; in some kind of race? ... I don't think so...I think the reason for the sentiment is that I feel a calmness. I don't feel overwhelmed by to-dos. I feel like I have time for the things that I enjoy and know are important...like journaling or cleaning the dishes or just sitting and looking out the window at the city. Wouldn't it be wonderful to have this feeling of calmness throughout the day? I think this is part of what meditation offers...gotta keep up with that." /></outline>

              <outline text="That's a bummer about the computer issues.               <outline text="I'm with you about the mappings being a little confusing. Part of what we're hoping to accomplish with the match ratios by category is to confirm the mappings that systems provided. For example, if you're showing extremely low match ratios for the &quot;Separated with Child in Household&quot; but normal match ratios for &quot;Separated&quot;, than we might be able to conclude that systems *really is* rating &quot;Separated With Child in Household&quot; as single. If the match ratios look similar between those two groups, however, we might need to do more investigating. " _note=" " />
              <outline text="As far as how these are *supposed* to be mapped, that's a good question and one we're trying to sort out. The only thing I see in the Rules is under Rule 12.A: &quot;For classification purposes, an operator is considered married if a widow or widower.&quot; If I were to guess at a mapping based on the descriptions, I would probably end up with what you have...but for now we're just trying to best understand how policies in those highlighted categories are actually being rated currently and then we'll work with Legal and other business partners to discuss whether any modifications need to be made." _note=" " />
              <outline text="Hope that helps, and let me know if you have any other questions or would like some more clarification!" />

              <outline text="&lt;b&gt;## Morning Pages #MorningPages&lt;/b&gt;" >
                <outline text="I often feel so rushed in the mornings. It's weird. No matter how much flexibility I have in terms of when I start my day and how early I get up, when I sit down to journal I feel like I need to rush through it and get on to my &quot;real work.&quot; This is a great example of the sort of anxiety that I'm realizing affects me much more than I ever thought. If anxiety = focusing on the future, then I'm often anxious. Even though in this case I'm not worrying in the traditional sense about what's next, I think any form of thinking about the future might be a form of &quot;worrying.&quot; It doesn't matter how many times I think &quot;stay in the moment!&quot; it always needs to be repeated. No matter how many times you sweep the floor, the dust comes back. You just have to keep sweeping." /></outline>

              <outline text="&lt;b&gt;## Morning Pages #MorningPages&lt;/b&gt;" >
                <outline text="I watched an interesting TED talk over the weekend. Harvard has been working on a 75-year longitudinal study of some Harvard students and kids from a poor area of Boston. After following the ~800 lives over the course of 75 years, they've come to some conclusions about what causes happiness and wellbeing. Basically, the conclusion is that the quality of relationships is by far the primary driver of health and happiness. More so than wealth or fame or anything else, relationships were the key. Basically, we all need to call our Moms more... :)" /></outline>
              <outline text="Book Quote" >

                <outline text="1. *Why do I stay up late?* Because it feels good." />
                <outline text="2. *Why does it feel good?* Because it gives me something to do after work." />
                <outline text="3. *Why does it have to go on for so long?* Because I feel like I want to have enough time to relax." />
                <outline text="4. *Why don't you relax earlier?* Because I'm too wound up from the work day to relax quickly." _note=" " />
                <outline text="In this case, I think I may have gotten to the bottom of it in only 4 questions...I think maybe I'm too wound up/stressed from the work day.               <outline text="&lt;b&gt;## Morning Pages #MorningPages&lt;/b&gt;" >
                <outline text="Christina and I went to St. Louis yesterday to see Nick and Kateri (and their new baby, Seraphia). It was pleasant for the most part. I noticed while hanging out with them how incredibly self-centered Kateri was being. Oof bad segue. I don't want to be mean about it, but I couldn't help but notice how Christina, Nick and I would be talking about something separate (e.g., Christina was talking through China trip pictures) and Kateri would just randomly say something about the baby clothes she was folding. It was like she couldn't go more than 60 seconds without bringing the attention back to her. I guess I understand *why* she's feeling that way...I mean, from her perspective nothing else matters except for her and her kid...and the whole world (from her perspective) has been fawning over her and her kid for the last week. It was a bit obnoxious as an outsider, but I can sympathize with the sentiment and I wonder if it's somewhat necessary. It's that motherly instinct that's so powerful and protective. I'm sure that instinct has saved a lot of children's lives over the centuries. I just wish it wasn't so obnoxious to others..." /></outline>
            </outline>
          </outline>

                <outline text="I just had a really wonderful evening with Christina. I think a little time apart probably created some excitement/chemistry. A leading scientist suggested doing exciting and new things regularly to release dopamine, making love regularly to release oxytocin, and resisting inclinations to cheat. I don't really have any strong impulses to cheat and I would certainly never *act* any any inclinations, but I do have attractions periodically. These attractions/fantasies tend to arise when I feel like I'm not getting the excitement and love-making needs fulfilled by Christina. So perhaps there are some things to be learned from this book that I can apply to my own life even though I'm not a cheater." /></outline>

              <outline text="&lt;b&gt;## Morning Pages #MorningPages&lt;/b&gt;" >
                <outline text="The last couple days have gone pretty well. Aside from drinking beer (damnit), I've been pretty good. I had a really productive day of writing yesterday. Something I read in The Subtle Art of Not Giving a Fuck yesterday stuck out to me. It's not the pleasures that we want that are indicative of our life, it's the pain that we want. What painful thing are we willing to take on in order to get the pleasures? It's a subtle twist to the no pain, no gain theory. I'll have to reflect on that some more. At first glance, though, I noticed that I wanted the pain of the long hours of hard work when I started at Allstate. I don't want the pain of the corporate politics, though, which could be why I've somewhat stalled. I'm happy to work long hours if the work itself is good. If the long hours are spent on bureaucratic minutia, though, I'm out. " /></outline>
            </outline>

              <outline text="&lt;b&gt;## Morning Pages #MorningPages&lt;/b&gt;" >

              <outline text="&lt;b&gt;## Morning Pages #MorningPages&lt;/b&gt;" >
                <outline text="I was listening to a Tony Robbins interview with John Wooden this morning, and I was amazed by how many of his comments and philosophies aligned with stoicism and what I've read by Ryan Holliday. He was talking about how all good things come through adversity (the obstacle is the way) and he's unbelievably humble (ego is the enemy). He never seemed to focus on outcomes, only the process. He just wanted each player to be the best that he could be and he wanted the team to be the best it could be, but the outcomes of winning and championships weren't as important. And interestingly, he was incredibly successful in the winning category. Goes to Scott Adams's idea of focusing on the system." /></outline>

          <outline text="&lt;b&gt;Inbox&lt;/b&gt;" >
            <outline text="[] Email @PC about climate change" >
              <outline text="Just saw Before the Flood..." />
              <outline text="For the insurance industry, this is obviously a huge risk. The pattern seems to be that dry areas will become drier, wet areas will become wetter, etc. and coastal areas will become very dangerous due to flooding, etc. e.g. Miami and the pumps. " />
              <outline text="But the likelihood that we'll be able to price for this accurately (and get those rates approved) seems extremely low. " />
              <outline text="So what are we to do in this situation?" />
              <outline text="It seems to me that our best course of action is to do what we can to prevent it from happening in the first place. If climate change continues, we're getting into a game that we can't possibly win. So the only way for us to continue to succeed is to avoid getting into the game in the first place. " />
              <outline text="We could perhaps reduce or eliminate our position in the homeowners market, but reducing premium in general is undesirable and shifting distrivutionally towards auto seems unwise as the rise of self-driving vehicles is imminent. " />
              <outline text="The oil and gas companies have lobbyists pushing against regulation on carbon taxes, etc. It seems the insurance industry is at least somewhat positioned to take the opposite stance in this issue and lobby *for* these kinds of measures that would help stop the momentum of climate change. What are we doing in this regard?" /></outline>
            <outline _complete="true" text="[X] Order National Geographic " />
            <outline _complete="true" text="[X] Set up InstaProofs" /></outline>
